08070nam a22009135i 9780812296921DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122969217 a10.9783/97808122969212doi  a(DE-B1597)563111  a(OCoLC)1145418711  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0160002bisacsh04a973.93309222300aAmerican Political Development and the Trump Presidency /ced. by Philip Rocco, Zachary Callen. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b4 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Governance: Politics, Policy, and Public Law00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: An Unsettled Time -- tPART I. PARTY LEGACIES AND THE 2016 ELECTION -- tChapter 1. The Scrambled Cycle: Realignment, PoliticalTime, and the Trump Presidency -- tChapter 2. The Limits of Policy Feedback as a Party- Building Tool -- tChapter 3. Presidential Nominations, Factional Conflict, and Prospects for Democratic Party Reform -- tPART II. RACE AND NATION IN TRUMP’S AMERICA -- tChapter 4. “One People, Under One God, Saluting One American Flag”: Trump, the Republican Party, and the Construction of American Nationalism -- tChapter 5. Trumpism and the Dual Tracks of American Polarization -- tChapter 6. Black Lives Matter from Wilson to Trump: Social Movements in APD -- tPART III. GOVERNANCE BY DISRUPTION -- tChapter 7. Whose President? Donald Trump and the Reagan Regime -- tChapter 8. The Policy State and the Post- truth Presidency -- tChapter 9. Finding Stability and Sustainability in the Trump Era: Medicare and the Affordable Care Act in Historical Perspective -- tChapter 10. State- Building as Parlor Trick: Trump, the Executive Branch, and the Politics of Deconstruction -- tPART IV. REFLECTIONS -- tChapter 11. Donald Trump and the End of American Politics -- tChapter 12. Trumpism and the Future of American Political Development -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLeading political scientists analyze the presidency of Donald Trump and its impact on the future of American politicsIn virtually all respects, the Trump presidency has disrupted patterns of presidential governance. However, does Trump signify a disruption, not merely in political style but in regime type in the United States? Assessing Trump's potential impact on democratic institutions requires an analysis of how these institutions—including especially the executive branch—have developed over time as well as an examination of the intersecting evolution of political parties, racial ideologies, and governing mechanisms. To explore how time and temporality have shaped the Trump presidency, editors Zachary Callen and Philip Rocco have brought together scholars in the research tradition of American political development (APD), which explicitly aims to consider how interactions between a range of institutions result in the shifting of power and authority in American politics, with careful attention paid to complex processes unfolding over time. By focusing on the factors that contribute to both continuity and change in American politics, APD is ideally situated to take a long view and help make sense of the Trump presidency.American Political Development and the Trump Presidency features contributions by leading political scientists grappling with the reasons why Donald Trump was elected and the meaning of his presidency for the future of American politics. Taking a historical and comparative approach—instead of viewing Trump's election as a singular moment in American politics—the essays here consider how Trump's election coincides with larger changes in democratic ideals, institutional structures, long-standing biases, and demographic trends. The Trump presidency, as this volume demonstrates, emerged from a gradual unsettling of ideational and institutional lineages. In turn, these essays consider how Trump's disruptive style of governance may further unsettle the formal and informal rules of American political life.Contributors: William D. Adler, Gwendoline Alphonso, Julia R. Azari, Zachary Callen, Megan Ming Francis, Daniel J. Galvin, Travis M. Johnston, Andrew S. Kelly, Robert C. Lieberman, Paul Nolette, Philip Rocco, Adam Sheingate, Chloe Thurston.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aPolitical development. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / General.2bisacsh  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.1 aAdler, William D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlphonso, Gwendoline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAzari, Julia R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCallen, Zachary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCallen, Zachary, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFrancis, Megan Ming, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalvin, Daniel J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Travis M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly, Andrew S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLieberman, Robert C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNolette, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRocco, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRocco, Philip, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSheingate, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThurston, Chloe N., econtr